column11: Is [approvedSymbol] a druggable gene?
column12: There are currently {number_of_approved_drugs} approved drugs which target {approvedSymbol}, indicating that it is a druggable gene.
column13: There are currently no approved drugs targeting {approvedSymbol}, but there are {number_of_potential_targets (not approved yet)} potential targets indicating that it may be a druggable gene.
column14: There are currently no approved drugs or potential targets for {approvedSymbol}, suggesting that it is not currently considered a druggable gene.
column15: There was one approved drug that targeted {approvedSymbol} but it has been withdrawn, suggesting complications in its druggability.
column16: There were {number_of_withdrawn_drugs} drugs that targeted {approvedSymbol} but they have been withdrawn, suggesting complications in its druggability.

column2: What are the allele frequencies of variant rs12206095 in PD?
column3: In the largest European genome-wide meta-analysis of Parkinson's disease from Nalls (2019), single nucleotide polymorphism rs12206095 has an alternate allele (A) frequency of 0.0317, and a reference allele (G) frequency of 0.9683.

column2: What are the allele frequencies of variant rs61769339 in AD?
column3:
In GWAS summary statistics for AD from Bellenguez (2022), single nucleotide polymorphism rs61769339 has an alternate allele (A) frequency of 0.1105 and reference
allele (G) frequency of 0.8895.

column2: What drugs target the gene ACACA?
column3:
There are no FDA approved drugs targeting the gene ACACA. However the following drugs are currently in various clinical trial stages: Firsocostat,
Pf-05175157, Clesacostat, and Olumacostat Glasaretil.

column2: Is Rotigotine approved to treat AD?
column3: Rotigotine has not been approved by the FDA as a treatment for Alzheimer's disease (AD), but it is currently undergoing evaluation in clinical trials for this purpose.

column2: Are there any CR1 SNPs that have a statistically significant association with Alzheimer's Disease?
column3:

• rs6656401 (GWAS P-value: 2.84E-33; b value: 0.1253)
• rs679515 (GWAS P-value: 5.15E-33; b value: 0.1244)
• rs4562624 (GWAS P-value: 1.11E-32; b value: 0.124)
• rs4844610 (GWAS P-value: 11.14E-32; b value: 0.1238)
• rs12037841 (GWAS P-value: 2.69E-32; b value: 0.1234)
• rs1408077 (GWAS P-value: 2.72E-31; b value: 0.1198)
• rs10863417 (GWAS P-value: 3.19E-31; b value: 0.1199)

column2: Are there any CR1 SNPs that have a statistically significant adjusted SMR p-value in association with Alzheimer's Disease and what tissues are they significant in?
column3:

• rs679515
    • Prefrontal cortex: Adjusted SMR multi-SNP P-value: 1.08E-12; HEIDI: 0.0028
    • Whole brain: Adjusted SMR multi-SNP P-value: 2.10E-12; HEIDI: 0.2568
    • Multi ancestry whole brain: Adjusted SMR multi-SNP P-value: 2.09E-15; HEIDI: 9.09e-08
    • Cortex: Adjusted SMR multi-SNP P-value: 4.46E-08; HEIDI: 0.9563

• rs1830763
    • Cortex: Adjusted SMR multi-SNP P-value: 3.83E-15; HEIDI: 0.0603
    • Cerebellum: Adjusted SMR multi-SNP P-value: 1.72E-08; HEIDI: 0.1092

• rs2093760
    • Caudate basal ganglia: Adjusted SMR multi-SNP P-value: 3.25E-08; HEIDI: 0.5329

• rs6697005

column2: How do the SMR associations between rs10256524 and Alzheimer's disease or Parkinson's disease risk differ across different brain tissues?
column3:
Here are the associations between rs10256524 and Alzheimer's disease or Parkinson's in different brain tissues:
Parkinson's Disease:
• In the Amygdala, rs10256524 exhibits a functionally significant association (Adjusted SMR multi-SNP P-value: 2.34e-06, HEIDI: 0.018).
• Similarly, in the Frontal Cortex BA9, rs10256524 shows a functionally significant association (Adjusted SMR multi-SNP P-value: 4.74e-07, HEIDI: 0.013).
Alzheimer's Disease:
• In both the Amygdala and the Frontal Cortex BA9, rs10256524 does not show a functionally significant association.

column2: How many synonym names does Sonidegib Phosphate have, and what are they?

column2: What is Aplenzin?
column3: Aplenzin, also known generically as bupropion hydrobromide, is used to treat major depressive disorder. It is a small molecule drug that acts as an inhibitor.

column2: What SNP is most significantly associated with PSP in spinal cord tissue?
column3: The most significantly associated SNP with Progressive supranuclear palsy in Spinal Cord eQTL omic data is rs8070723, located in the LRRC37A2 gene, with a multi SNP SMR p value of 2.163e-11 and a HEIDI value of 1.775e-07.

column2: Is the gene GRIA4 targeted by multiple different approved drugs to treat PD?
column3:
Yes, the gene GRIA4 is targeted by two drugs for the treatment of PD:
•Topiramate
•Perampanel

column2: Has the FDA approved any drugs targeting the gene APOE for the treatment of neurodegenerative diseases?
column3: No, as of now, the FDA hasn't approved any drugs targeting the gene APOE for the treatment of neurodegenerative diseases.

column2: What is the top SNP in blood for Lewy Body Dementia?
column3: The top SNP when analyzing whole blood in Lewy Body Dementia is rs17561351, located in the PVRL2 gene, with a multi SNP SMR p value of 2.638e-25 and a p Heidi of 2.172e-14

column2: What is the allele frequency of the SNP rs2075650 in the context of Parkinson's disease?
column3:
In the largest European genome-wide meta-analysis of Parkinson's disease from Nalls (2019), single nucleotide polymorphism rs2075650 has an alternate allele (G) frequency of 0.131 and reference
allele (A) frequency of 0.869.

column2: What are the names of the genes that are targeted by the drug Levodopa in the treatment of Parkinson's disease?
column3: In the context of Parkinson's disease, the drug Levodopa targets the gene dopamine receptor D3.

column2: Which genes are targeted by the drug Dasatinib in the treatment of Alzheimer's disease?
column3: The drug Dasatinib has not been approved by the FDA as a treatment for Alzheimer's disease (AD), but it is currently undergoing evaluation in clinical trials for this purpose. However, there are 15 proposed gene targets: KIT, BCR, ABL1, PDGFRB, SRC, FRK, YES1, BLK, SRMS, LCK, LYN, FYN, EPHA2, FGR, and HCK.

column2: how many mechanisms of action does the drug Brentuximab Vedotin have?
column3:
The drug Brentuximab Vedotin has two mechanisms of action: Tumor necrosis factor receptor superfamily member 8 inhibitor and         
Tubulin inhibitor.

column2: Are there any specific alleles within the gene CHRM3 associated with increased susceptibility to developing Alzheimer's disease?
column3: No, there are no alleles within the gene CHRM3 that are significantly associated with an increased susceptibility to developing Alzheimer's disease based on AD GWAS data.

column2: Tell me about GWAS in Alzheimer's Disease.
column3:
A Genome-wide association study (GWAS) identifys risk alleles that are associated with a particular disease. According to the largest European meta-GWAS of Alzheimer's disease (Bellenguez, 2022), there are 5,625 SNPs that were found to be significantly associated with an increased risk of Alzheimer's disease.  Here are the top 10 SNPs:

• rs117310449 (GWAS P-value: 3.26E-115; b value: 0.7701; nearest gene: TOMM40)
• rs144261139 (GWAS P-value: 5.17E-111; b value: 0.7545; nearest gene: NECTIN2)
• rs139644294 (GWAS P-value: 1.53E-94; b value: -0.2252; unspecified nearest gene)
• rs6733839 (GWAS P-value: 6.48E-90; b value: 0.1686; nearest gene: BIN1;CYP27C1)
• rs537741299 (GWAS P-value: 8.59E-84; b value: 0.8705; unspecified nearest gene)
• rs61679753 (GWAS P-value: 2.28E-83; b value: -0.5412; nearest gene: TOMM40)
• rs1160983 (GWAS P-value: 4.99E-83; b value: -0.5399; nearest gene: TOMM40)
• rs111784051 (GWAS P-value: 1.01E-82; b value: -0.5545; nearest gene: TOMM40)
• rs7254892 (GWAS P-value: 7.74E-82; b value: -0.5173; nearest gene: NECTIN2)
• rs79701229 (GWAS P-value: 5.34E-81; b value: 0.7038; nearest gene: NECTIN2)

column2: Which tissues express genes with SNPs that are associated with PD?
column3: Out of the 22 tissues tested, 21 expressed genes with SNPs that are significantly associated with Parkinson's Disease (PD). The tissue expressing genes with the highest number of significant SNPs was the whole brain, with 220 significant SNPs. The spinal cord had the highest proportion of significant SNPs relative to the total SNPs, with a proportional significance of 0.002.

column2: What is the patent number associated with Sonidegib Phosphate?
column3: There are 3 patent numbers associated with the drug Sonidegib Phosphate; 8178563, 10266523, and 8063043.

column2: Which morphinan scaffold derived medications have been modified for extended-release (ER) or sustained-release (SR) using Polistirex?
column3: Hydrocodone, Codeine, and Dextromethorphan are all morphinan scaffold derived medications that have modified formulations using Polistirex to extend their release time, creating extended-release (ER) or sustained-release (SR) versions of these medications.
